                <h2>A Gentle Balance: Observations on Daily Life in Taiwan</h2>
                <h3>1. The "Reserving Seats" Culture</h3>
                <p>In Taiwan's coffee shops or food courts, you often see a strange sight: a phone, an umbrella, or even an expensive bag left on a table with no one sitting there. This is not lost property; it is Taiwan's unique <strong>"occupying seats" culture</strong>.</p>
                <p>This reflects an extremely high level of <strong>Social Trust</strong>. Many foreigners living in Taiwan often develop a habit of "negligence," thinking that even if they lose their wallet, a kind person will take it to the police station.</p>
                <p><strong>A Gentle Warning:</strong> While Taiwan is indeed safe, crime is not non-existent. Please enjoy this sense of security but do not lose your basic alertness. Looking after valuables is still a traveler's responsibility.</p>
