                <h3>1. The Magic Particles (Sentence-final particles)</h3>
                <p>If you know a little Mandarin, you will find that Taiwanese speech sounds particularly "soft." We rely heavily on <strong>Sentence-final particles</strong> to modify our tone. Without them, we feel we sound too fierce or serious.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>La (Âï¶):</strong> Emphasizing or pleading, sometimes with a bit of whining or helplessness. <br><em>Example: "Hao-la" (Okay, fine / Come on).</em></li>
                    <li><strong>Ne (Êçè / Neh):</strong> Surprise, seeking agreement, or strengthening tone. <br><em>Example: "Zhen-de-neh" (It really is true!).</em></li>
                    <li><strong>O (Âñî / Oh):</strong> Reminder, warning, or friendly suggestion. <br><em>Example: "Xiao-xin-oh" (Be careful~).</em></li>
                    <li><strong>Ye (ËÄ∂ / Yay):</strong> Uncertainty or finding something interesting. <br><em>Example: "Hao-xiang-shi-ye" (I think that might be right).</em></li>
